{
  "title": "2.6 THEORIES OF RESOURCE-USE CONFLICT",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "37defd0d30a2aefc",
      "text": "There are several theories of resource use conflict. These include:"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "28292795e868e79a",
      "text": "**(a) Tragedy of the Commons** "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "3c54ba5171b27974",
      "text": "Originally, an economic theory, the tragedy of the commons describes a situation whereby a resource shared either by individuals or a group of people is used or depleted in a careless and selfish way with no consideration whatsoever either for the resource or the long term interest of its users. The concept is often used in respect of sustainable development.  "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "caae1d44c63e5895",
      "text": "Hardins (1968 & 1988) used the term in analyzing the problem of resource use conflict and observed that if an individual or a group, acting in an irrational self-interest, uses a common resource for its own gain and with no regard for others, such resource would eventually be depleted. He added that common land tenure systems in Africa encourages the degradation of natural resources which was inevitable because while herders held animals individually, the range was unregulated common property and farmers enjoy preferential treatment in its use."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "a6a4ee7433b76274",
      "text": "In critiquing Handins’ work, Ostrom (1990) argues that the expression, tragedy of the commons, symbolizes the degradation of the environment as a result of many individuals using scarce resources with little or no regard for its sustainability."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "765122bcaacff699",
      "text": "**(b) Theory of Environmental Scarcity** "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ee05d0df1d67dad9",
      "text": "Another theory is the environmental scarcity theory which was articulated by Hommer-Dixon (1991, 1994, 1995 & 1999) and Gizewski (1997). It attempts to link conflict among resource users, with increase in tension arising from growing vulnerability to insecurity of their livelihoods. To them, resource-use conflict between multiple resource users was inevitable as competition for natural resources becomes stiffer."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "be7d13953c5295c0",
      "text": "Hommer-Dixon contended that environmental change, population growth and unequal social distribution are the three main sources of scarcity, which leads to violent conflict. He considered the political economy of resource distribution and argued that environmental change and population growth are the most pernicious when they intervene with unequal resource distribution. (Hommer-Dixon 1994)."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ab8cfafad0a9d067",
      "text": "The strong relationship between environmental resources and conflict has engaged the attention of scholars like Pacial, Hommer-Dixon and Gleditsch. Hommer-Dixon’s theory of eco-violence observes that in many developing countries, large populations depend on four key environmental resources that are fundamental to crop production. These include fresh water, cropland, forests and fish. Scarcity or shrinking of these resources arising from misuse, overuse, or degradation triggers off conflicts. He added that decrease in quality and quantity of renewable resources, population growth and unequal access to resources act singly or jointly to impact negatively on certain populations. The affected group may be forced to migrate to new locations and such migrating groups often trigger conflicts (Hommer- Dixon & Blitt, 1998). "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "cd6420647eacbc16",
      "text": "**(c) Greed versus Grievance Theory**"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "46a41a131bd61b49",
      "text": "The greed versus grievance theory propounded by Colliar (2001) tried to explain wider processes of conflict and queried the role of scarcity in conflict causation. It is Colliar’s view that conflicts were related to “proxies of greed rather than proxies of grievance”. In other words, economies based on primary commodities and large pool of poorly educated young men rather than issues of inequality, lack of political rights are drivers of conflict. Baechlar (1999) argues that there is no direct causal relationship between scarcity and conflict. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b6c2e35ecfdbf6c1",
      "text": "He used the analogy of two or more actors having common interest to use a piece of land and their interest automatically includes who (uses it), why, how, and when. He further observes that people in all cultures have always tried to overcome scarcity of resources in their own way by using their societal and institutional mechanisms to resolve their differences rather than resorting to violence. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "491f2bf0973aa3c4",
      "text": "Critics of the scarcity theory have further argued that nature is not scarce and that scarcity is a man-made phenomenon connected to factors such as power, politics, distribution of resources as well as drawing boundaries and international politics (Shettima &Tar 2008). "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "bc1c49ca4ba6a0eb",
      "text": "**(d) Political Economy Theory**"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "01b818b0eb1ae813",
      "text": "Hildyard (1999) used the political economy theory to explain environmental conflict. According to him, individuals and groups get access to what resources and means of livelihood on the basis of distribution of political and economic power within the society. He also argued that scarcity and hunger which may lead to group conflict are not always natural but are socially constructed, politically manipulated and economically distributed. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "0c68bbca197de8df",
      "text": "Hildyard concluded that even when there is scarcity, the distribution of its impact is socially determined. What these critics are saying, in effect, is that scarcity does not always lead to conflict (especially violent conflict) among resource users. Scarcity, according to them, has always been present in all human history and each society has, over time, devised modalities for addressing such scarcity. Hence, scarcity should not ordinarily degenerate into conflict, not to talk of violent confrontation. "
    }
  ],
